<h2>üí° Theory of Value Investing</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Value Investing</strong> was first proposed by Benjamin Graham, who is known as the "Father of Security Analysis".
        <ul>
            <li>Core theory:
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Company = Business</strong>, buying stocks is equivalent to buying part of the business.</li>
                    <li><strong>Price vs Value</strong>: Market prices fluctuate daily, but the long-term value of companies is relatively stable.</li>
                    <li><strong>Margin of Safety</strong>: Only when the price is far below the value is it worth buying.</li>
                </ol>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Buffett improved on Graham's foundation:
        <ul>
            <li>Not only buy at low prices, but also buy "good companies" ‚Üí deep moats, strong cash flow, and long-term growth.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>

<blockquote>
    üìå Summary: Value investing is not about chasing short-term ups and downs, but about selecting companies that "can continue to make money" and holding them for the long term.
</blockquote>

